issue.body:
Typeshed currently treats `collections.abc.Callable` as equivalent to `typing.Callable`, but they aren't

```python
import typing
from collections import abc
assert isinstance(abc.Callable, type)  # ✅
assert isinstance(typing.Callable, type)  # ❌
```

This causes a very annoying bug: https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/14014

[`collections.abc.Callable` is a subclass of `ABCMeta`:](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/0823f4361850145152a94e9086bede6a000d8a4a/Lib/_collections_abc.py#L541-L555
), a real type that can be used in match-case and isinstance/issubclass.

```python
class Callable(metaclass=ABCMeta):


    __slots__ = ()


    @abstractmethod
    def __call__(self, *args, **kwds):
        return False


    @classmethod
    def __subclasshook__(cls, C):
        if cls is Callable:
            return _check_methods(C, "__call__")
        return NotImplemented


    __class_getitem__ = classmethod(_CallableGenericAlias)
```
